232 21 CHAP. 68. Alesiam: this famous fortress (now called Alise Ste.Reine) was on the territory lying just north of the Haeduan frontier. Its natural advantages— summed up in the succeeding chapters— are thus described ε

“ Alesia, like Gergovia, is on a hill sloping off all round, with steep and, in placeS, precipitous sides. It lies between two small riverS, both of which fall into the Brenne, and thence into the Seine. Into this peninsula, with the rivers on each side of him, Vercingetorix had thrown himself with 80‚ooo men. Alesia as a position was impregnable except to famine. ’ The water supply was secure. The position was of extraordinary strength. The rivers formed natural trenches. Below the town, to the west, they ran parallel for three miles through an open alluvial plain before they reached the Brenne.
